# Node.js Streams Practice — File Copy using ReadStream & WriteStream

This file demonstrates how to copy a large file efficiently using
Node.js Streams, instead of loading the entire file into memory at once.

## What this code does

1. **Setup**
   - Creates a `docs` folder if it doesn't exist
   - Creates a sample `HugeFile.txt` (1000 lines) for testing, if not already present

2. **ReadStream**
   - Opens `HugeFile.txt` in stream mode using `fs.createReadStream()`
   - Reads the file in small chunks (default 64KB per chunk) instead of
     loading the whole file into memory

3. **WriteStream**
   - Opens `CopyFile.txt` in stream mode using `fs.createWriteStream()`
   - Writes each chunk received from the ReadStream into this file

4. **Combining Read + Write**
   - Every time a `'data'` chunk is received from ReadStream,
     it is immediately written to WriteStream using `.write(chunk)`
   - Once ReadStream finishes (`'end'` event), `writeStream.end()` is
     called to properly close the write stream

## Key Events Used

| Event      | Stream       | When it fires                                  |
|------------|--------------|-------------------------------------------------|
| `'open'`   | ReadStream   | When the file is successfully opened            |
| `'data'`   | ReadStream   | Every time a new chunk is read                  |
| `'end'`    | ReadStream   | After the entire file has been read             |
| `'error'`  | Both         | If any error occurs (missing file, permissions) |
| `'finish'` | WriteStream  | After all data has been written successfully    |

## Why Streams instead of `readFile`/`writeFile`?

- `fs.readFile()` loads the **entire file into memory (RAM)** before
  processing — not efficient for large files (videos, logs, big datasets)
- `fs.createReadStream()` / `fs.createWriteStream()` process data in
  **small chunks**, keeping memory usage low and performance high

## Proof that Streams are Async

The last line of the script logs a message immediately, **before** any
stream events fire. Run the file and check the console output order —
this confirms streams work in the background without blocking the
main thread.

## How to Run

```bash
node streamPractice.js
```

After running, check the `docs` folder:
- `HugeFile.txt` — the original sample file
- `CopyFile.txt` — the copied file (created via streams)

## Possible Improvements

- Use `.pipe()` instead of manually handling `'data'` events:
  ```javascript
  readStream.pipe(writeStream);
  ```
  This does the same job in one line — recommended shortcut once you're
  comfortable with the manual event-based approach above.
- Add file size logging using `fs.statSync()` to compare source vs copy
- Convert to `async/await` style using `fs.promises` for cleaner code